column1: The stable, unique identifier for a study that never changes, even if other study metadata changes (like the study name, short name, owner, or project). Example: STUDY_SCA
column2: Use studyID as the anchor, plus a persistent row identifier to identify a specific file/version, etc.
column3: Enter a unique identifier for the selection made.
column4: Indicates the level of entity to which a metadata value applies (e.g., individual participant or population summary).
column5: Specifies whether a metadata value represents individual-level data or an aggregate summary
column6: Identifies the population described by the metadata (e.g., study-wide, cohort, or study arm).
column7: The time period or periods during which data were collected for a study, cohort, or variable, summarized at an aggregate level.
column8: Earliest calendar year of data collection
column9: Latest calendar year of data collection
column10: Explicit list of years, if non-continuous. Four-digit integers (e.g., 2019)
column11: Seasons during which data were collected
column13: The age or ages of a participant at the time of enrollment or at defined enrollment-related timepoints in a study, including single ages, age ranges, or multiple ages associated with longitudinal or staged enrollment.
column14: A named study milestone at which enrollment occurs (e.g., baseline, re-enrollment, extension phase).
column15: The physical or situational setting in which a data collection activity or assessment is administered. Describes where data collection occurs, not how, who, or what. Intended for general or summary-level reporting, not per-participant metadata.
column16: The primary mode by which data were collected for a variable or assessment.
column17: Enrollment wave (baseline, follow-up, etc.). Identifies the recruitment phase or wave during which participants were enrolled in a study, reflecting distinct enrollment periods defined by study design or operational milestones.
column18: The recruitment or enrollment wave(s) represented in the study population.
column19: A stable identifier for a defined recruitment wave or enrollment phase within a study. Examples: WAVE:1, WAVE:2, WAVE:PILOT, WAVE:EXTENSION
column20: A stable identifier for a defined time period during which data collection occurred under consistent procedures or conditions. Examples: PERIOD:BASELINE, PERIOD:FOLLOWUP_6MO, PERIOD:COVID_ERA, PERIOD:2020_2021
column21: A stable identifier for a defined study arm, group, or condition assignment used to structure participant enrollment, intervention, or comparison. Examples: ARM:CONTROL, ARM:TREATMENT_A, ARM:HIGH_RISK, ARM:CASE, ARM:COMPARATOR
column22: A stable identifier for a defined component of a study (e.g., wave, arm, period) used to scope metadata summaries.
column23: The category of study subcomponent identified by studyComponentID (e.g., wave, arm, period), used to indicate what kind of study structure the component represents for scoping metadata summaries.
column24: Years since original cohort enrollment. Summarizes the amount of time elapsed since original cohort enrollment for which participant data are available. Values can be in: minYears, maxYears, years.
column26: The manner in which a digital assessment or data collection activity is administered to participants.
column27: EMA schedule type. Valid values: free text, OR Multiple, Varies, Unknown
column28: Frequency of prompts. Valid values: free text, OR Multiple, Varies, Unknown
column29: Response window (minutes). Valid values: free text, OR Multiple, Varies, Unknown.
column30: Indicates whether participant enrollment occurs continuously over time rather than within a fixed recruitment window.
column31: The calendar year in which study recruitment or data collection began. Use "Unknown" if not available.
column32: A summary description of the study’s burst-based sampling structure (bursts, timing, follow-up cadence, and recruitment waves).
column33: The number of distinct burst periods of intensive measurement scheduled per participant.
column35: The planned duration of each burst period of intensive measurement.
column36: The planned frequency at which bursts occur across the study timeline.
column38: The planned amount of time between participant follow-up assessments, visits, or measurement periods.
column39: Indicates whether individual observations/records include a date or timestamp of data collection.
